The World Tree
The World Tree (known in High Aetheric as Sylvandor Prime or simply The Heart) is the single most important living entity on the planet of Aetheria. It is not merely a tree — it is the planetary soul and the primary engine of all magic.
Origin and Nature
The World Tree existed before the Twelve Gods gave it form. It is a colossal, sentient organism whose roots stretch deep into the planet’s ley-line network, while its branches pierce the sky and even touch other planes of existence. Its trunk is so vast that entire elven cities are grown within and upon it. At its peak, during the Golden Age, it stood taller than the highest mountains and glowed with pure golden-white light visible from space.
Its leaves are crystalline, its bark shimmers with living runes, and its sap is pure liquid mana. Every major ley-line on Aetheria originates from its root system.
Current State (After 9,000 Years of War)
The World Tree is wounded but not dead.
The Great War and the ten millennia of constant conflict have taken a terrible toll:

Large sections of its root network are corrupted or severed by demonic incursions.
Many of its greatest branches have been burned, broken, or twisted into Corrupted Worldthorns (massive, bleeding black trees that still exist in the Blighted Reach and Crimson Canopy).
Mana production has dropped dramatically — roughly 35-40% less than during the Golden Age.
This weakening is the main reason the Twelve Gods began secretly syphoning mana from Earth.

Despite its injuries, the Tree still sustains all life and magic on the planet. Without it, Aetheria would slowly die.
Location
The physical heart of the World Tree lies in the Eternal Glade, deep within the Verdant Court (the most powerful High Forest Enclave). However, its influence and root systems extend across the entire planet:

Major surface manifestations exist in every continent.
The largest above-ground portion is in Sylvandor (elven continent).
Underground, its deepest roots reach into dwarven territories and even touch demonic realms.

Religious and Cultural Significance

Elves: Consider themselves the Tree’s chosen children. Many High Forest rituals involve direct communion with it. The Veiling is believed by some to have been an attack on the Tree’s connection to elven memory.
Beastkin: View it as the ultimate Primal Spirit and source of all totems.
Dwarves: Respect it as the “Root of the Stone Father” but are wary of its influence on the surface world.
Humans: See it mostly as a mythical source of magic. Some sects (especially in Vaelor and Whitestone) have begun pilgrimages to it.
The Twelve Gods: Sylvandor (the god) is its direct divine aspect. The gods treat the Tree with deep care — it is the main reason they are finally stirring from apathy.

Powers and Properties
Even in its weakened state, the World Tree can:

Generate ambient mana across the planet.
Awaken ancient guardians (treants, nature spirits, and living constructs).
Grant blessings to those it deems worthy (very rare in the current age).
Heal the land slowly over centuries.
Open temporary spirit paths and ley-line portals.

Current Threats

Demonic Corruption — Especially in the eastern parts of Sylvandor and the Bloodplains on Pangara.
Over-harvesting — Some human and dwarven groups secretly extract sap or roots for powerful artifacts.
Mana Imbalance — The gods’ syphoning from Earth is helping, but it creates dangerous fluctuations and thin spots in reality.

Many scholars and archdruids believe that if the World Tree suffers one more major wound (or if the mana syphoning goes wrong), it could trigger a Second Shattering.
